{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"9b633849-08ec-411e-afeb-20377ba55051","content":"Use the `--filter` option with a class name filter:\n\n```bash\ndotnet test --filter \"FullyQualifiedName~SmsNotificationTests\"\n```\n\nThis matches any test whose fully qualified name contains `SmsNotificationTests`, which will run both `SendSms_HealthCheck` and `SendSms_ValidPhone_Succeeds`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d1aaca5b-8e75-4ea7-828d-daecf40c0f5f","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to run only the `SmsNotificationTests` class from this TUnit project. TUnit uses its own test adapter and filtering. With `dotnet test`, you can use the `--filter` option to filter by class name.\n\nFor TUnit, the filter syntax uses `FullyQualifiedName` or `ClassName`. The standard MSTest/xUnit/NUnit filter syntax works:\n\n```\ndotnet test --filter \"ClassName=SmsNotificationTests\"\n```\n\nor using fully qualified name:\n\n```\ndotnet test --filter \"FullyQualifiedName~SmsNotificationTests\"\n```\n\nTUnit uses its own test adapter but supports the standard dotnet test filter expressions. \n\nThe `FullyQualifiedName~` approach with the contains operator is the most reliable way to target the test class.","outputTokens":279,"requestId":"1BC2:315D54:4B88F9:56458C:6A03D687"},"id":"7a25caa7-a343-4d01-afe3-7372e3373480","timestamp":"2026-05-13T01:40:31.732Z","parentId":"55717b85-b673-47d8-9073-4ad67492bf3b"}
